Lieutenant-Colonel '''Sir Francis D'Oyly''' {{postnominals|KCB}} (1776 – 18 June 1815) was a British Army officer. He was the third son of [[Matthias D'Oyly|Matthias]] and Mary D'Oyly.<ref name="mem">{{cite web |url=http://www.ukniwm.org.uk/server/show/conMemorial.58535/fromUkniwmSearch/1 |title=Lt Col Sir Francis D'oyly Kcb |website=Imperial War Museums}}</ref>

Commissioned into the [[Grenadier Guards|1st Regiment of Guards]], D'Oyly served with them during the [[Anglo-Russian invasion of Holland|1799 Anglo-Russian expedition to the Netherlands]] in 1799. He returned to the Netherlands in the [[Walcheren Campaign]] of 1809. On 2 July 1811, both he and his brother Henry were promoted from captains to majors in the army.<ref>{{London Gazette | issue=16500 |page=1203 | date=29 June 1811}}</ref> On 6 October 1812, he was given command of a company in the Guards as a brevet major after the death of Lt-Col. Colquitt.<ref>{{London Gazette | issue=16654 |page=2018 |date=3 October 1812}}</ref> He then served under the Duke of Wellington in [[Peninsular War|the British Army's campaign in the Spanish Peninsula and France]],<ref name="mem" /> after which he was made a [[Order of the Bath|KCB]].<ref>{{London Gazette | issue=16972 |page=20 | date=4 January 1815}}</ref><ref>{{London Gazette | issue=16977 |page=103 | date=21 January 1815}}</ref> He again served under Wellington during [[Waterloo Campaign|the Hundred Days]] and was killed at the [[battle of Waterloo]].<ref name="mem" /> 

